{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778080758,"nonce":"E8kufTr1slo+Xh6d9FWJJqk59jk=","title":"H-infinity Riccati teacher: behavioural cloning + fine-tune","message":"Use the production H∞ Riccati K (`src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py`) as a teacher policy and distil into a neural policy.\n\n**Pipeline:**\n1. Solve H∞ Riccati on the rlrmp linearised plant at γ near γ\\*. Get K(t).\n2. Roll out K under the same task distribution; record (state, control) pairs.\n3. Behavioural-clone: minimise MSE between neural policy output and K-prescribed control.\n4. Fine-tune on the standard rlrmp loss (running_cost) — this restores task performance with the inflated-K bias preserved.\n\n**Why this matters:**\nThis is the highest-confidence existence proof for the velocity signature in a neural policy on rlrmp. If the distilled policy reproduces the +5–13%% Δv that the analytic K predicts, the gap closure is purely from K-shape; if not, there's a representational issue we need to chase.\n\n**Tests:**\n- Distilled policy on rlrmp parameters reproduces the H∞ Riccati's predicted Δv (within fine-tune tolerance).\n- Generalises to unseen perturbations comparably to APT-trained baseline.\n\nReferences: synthesis_review §4.3 phase B, §11 step 3. Umbrella: b557d4e. Depends on 5a44bd3 (production Riccati, merged).","files":null}]}